The paper deals with data structures for compressed strings and their applications, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The use of signature encoding and LZ77 factorization also suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT) and data compression (cs.CC). The paper also presents efficient construction algorithms for straight-line programs, which are commonly used in grammar-based compression, indicating a possible connection to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). Finally, the paper discusses applications of the data structures in natural language processing and bioinformatics, which suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
